fields.subvisa_body:
Student visa (subclass 500) is a temporary visa for international students who want to participate in any academic course in Australia. This visa lasts for the duration of their study program, which is usually up to 5 years.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be enrolled in a full-time course registered on CRICOS in Australia
  • •  You must be age 6 or older to apply for this visa
  • •  You must have made welfare arrangements if you are under 18 years old
  • •  You must be a genuine temporary entrant with an intention of returning back to your country after your study
  • •  You must meet health and character requirements
  • •  You must hold an eligible substantive visa if in Australia

 

Extra documents you need to present while applying for Student visa:

  • •  Evidence of enrolment
  • •  Personal statement addressing the Genuine Temporary Entrant (GTE) requirement
  • •  All prior academic or work experience documents
  • •  IELTS records
  • •  Evidence of financial stability (enough for the cost of your living, study courses, and travel expenses)
  • •  Adequate health insurance coverage by Overseas Student Health Cover (OSHC)

Student Guardian visa (subclass 590) is a temporary visa for those who would like to visit Australia to support and care for a Student visa holder below the age of 18, or anyone older due to exceptional circumstances.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must  be the visa holder’s parent, custodian, or relative who is 21 years or older
  • •  You must have enough money to support yourself and the student during your stay
  • •  You must be able to provide accommodation, welfare and other support
  • •  You must be a genuine temporary entrant
  • •  You must meet health and character requirements

Training visa (subclass 407) is a temporary visa that allows you to take part in workplace-based occupational training activities to improve your skills in the field of your study or job, or in a professional development training program in Australia. 

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be sponsored, and your sponsor must be approved as a temporary activities sponsor
  • •  Your sponsor must nominate you to participate in any occupational training
  • •  You must be 18 years or older
  • •  You must be able to financially support yourself and your accompanying family member
  • •  You must be a genuine temporary entrant
  • •  You must meet health and character requirements

The Temporary Graduate (Subclass 485) visa allows international students to live, study and work after they have finished their studies in Australia. This visa has two streams namely, Graduate Work Stream and Post Study Work Stream.

Temporary Graduate Visa (subclass 485) is a temporary visa for recently graduated international students from universities of Australia who would like to live, study and work here in Australia.

Under this visa, you can choose from two streams: Graduate Work Stream & Post-Study Work Stream

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be under age 50
  • •  You must hold an eligible visa at present
  • •  You must have held a student visa in the last 6 months
  • •  You must have a recent qualification in the CRICOS-registered courses
  • •  You must nominate a single stream only (one cannot change the stream after they apply for this visa)
  • •  You must demonstrate decent English language ability, either through holding certain countries’ passports or undertaking English ability tests

Skilled Independent Visa (subclass 189) is a permanent visa for invited global workers with highly-demanded skill sets and New Zealand citizens who have demonstrated commitment and contribution to Australia who would like to permanently live and work anywhere in Australia. 

Under this visa, you can choose from two streams: Points-Tested Stream & New Zealand Stream

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • For Point-tested Stream:
  •  
  • •  You must be invited to apply
  • •  You must be under 45 to invite
  • •  Your occupation must be on the relevant list of eligible skilled occupations
  • •  You don’t need a sponsor or nominator

 

  • For New Zealand Stream:
  •  
  • •  You must hold a New Zealand Special Category (subclass 444) visa
  • •  You must have lived in Australia, at least, for the last 5 years, i.e. you must have started living here on or before 19 February, 2016
  • •  Your taxable income must be at least the minimum income threshold of AUD 53,900, unless any case of exemptions
  •     ° If you have applied for this visa on or after 1 July, 2021, you must have met the minimum income threshold for at least 3 completed financial years in the last 5 years of your application date. One of these years must be the recent completed financial year.
  •     ° If you have applied for this visa before 1 July, 2021, you must have met the minimum income threshold for each 4 completed financial years prior to your application date.

Skilled Nominated Visa (subclass 190) is a permanent visa for the nominated skilled workers who would like to live and work in Australia as permanent residents. You must be nominated by an Australian state or territory government agency for this visa.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be nominated and invited to apply for this visa
  • •  You must have an occupation on the relevant skilled list
  • •  You must have a suitable skills assessment for the occupation
  • •  You must be below the age of 45 before you are invited to apply
  • •  You must be able to score 65 points or above

Global Talent visa (subclass 858) is a permanent visa for internationally recognized talents who are prominent in their field of expertise or highly skilled in specified sectors. They can live, study, work or sponsor eligible relatives for permanent residency in Australia under this visa. 

Under this visa, there are two pathways: Global Talent Pathway & Distinguished Talent Pathway

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  Your contribution in professional, sports, arts, or academic fields must raise Australia’s economic or social, or cultural value
  • •  You must be able to easily obtain employment and establish well in your field of expertise
  • •  You must be internationally renowned with a record of exceptional achievement in
  •     ° A profession
  •     ° A sport
  •     ° The arts
  •     ° Academics and Research
  • •  For the Global Talent pathway, you must be highly skilled in one of these sectors:
  •     ° Resources
  •     ° Energy
  •     ° Health Industries
  •     ° Defense, Advanced Manufacturing and Space
  •     ° Circular Economy
  •     ° DigiTech
  •     ° Infrastructure and Tourism
  •     ° Financial Service and Fintech
  •     ° Education
  • •  For the Global Talent pathway, you must have the ability to attract salary at or above the high-income threshold of AUD 153,600
  • •  You must be nominated by either an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen or an Australian organization with a national reputation in the same field as you to apply for this visa
  • •  You must have functional English and must meet health and character requirements

Visitor visa (subclass 600) is a temporary visa that lets visitors and tourists visit Australia for personal or business purposes. You can stay up to 3 or 6 or 12 months, as specified in your visa.

  • Under this visa, you can choose from 5 streams:
  •  •  Tourist stream
  •  •  Sponsored Family stream
  •  •  Business Visitor stream
  •  •  Approved Destination Status stream
  •  •  Frequent Traveller stream

 

  • General key eligibility criteria:
  •  •  You must be a genuine visitor
  •  •  You must have enough funds to support your stay and leave
  •  •  You must meet health and character requirements

Aged Parent Visa (subclass 804) is a permanent visa that lets an aged parent of a settled Australian citizen or an Australian permanent resident or an eligible New Zealand citizen stay in Australia. You can enroll in Australia’s public healthcare scheme, Medicare, sponsor your family members for other Australian visas, and, if eligible, apply for Australian citizenship with this visa. 

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be in Australia while applying for this visa
  • •  You must be sponsored, which in this case is usually by an eligible child who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen
  • •  You must be old enough to receive the age pension in Australia, which usually is 65-67 years old, depending on your date of birth
  • •  You must not hold a Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 870)
  • •  You must meet the balance-of-family test
  • •  You must be able to obtain assurance of support
  • •  You must meet the health and character requirement

Contributory Aged Parent visa (subclass 884) is a temporary visa that lets an aged parent of a settled Australian citizen or an Australian permanent resident or an eligible New Zealand citizen stay in Australia for a stated period of time.

You can work or study in Australia, but you will not be granted any government support. This is the first step to apply for a permanent Contributory Aged Parent visa (subclass 864)

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be in Australia while applying for this visa
  • •  You must be sponsored, which in this case is usually by an eligible child who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen
  • •  You must be old enough to receive the age pension in Australia, which usually is 65-67 years old, depending on your date of birth
  • •  You must not hold a Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 870)
  • •  You must meet the balance-of-family test
  • •  You must meet the health and character requirement

Contributory Aged Parent visa (subclass 864) is a permanent visa that lets an aged parent of a settled Australian citizen or an Australian permanent resident or an eligible New Zealand citizen stay in Australia.

You can work or study in Australia, and can be eligible to enroll in Australia’s public healthcare scheme, Medicare. If you have already applied for a Contributory Aged Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 884), a (subclass 864) visa will help you to ease the cost of visa over a number of years

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be in Australia while applying for this visa
  • •  You must be sponsored, which in this case is usually by an eligible child who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen
  • •  You must be old enough to receive the age pension in Australia, which usually is 65-67 years old, depending on your date of birth
  • •  You must not hold a Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 870)
  • •  You must meet the balance-of-family test
  • •  You must be able to obtain assurance of support
  • •  You must meet the health and character requirement

Contributory Parent visa (subclass 173) is a temporary visa that lets a parent of a settled Australian citizen or an Australian permanent resident or an eligible New Zealand citizen stay in Australia.

You can work or study in Australia under this visa, but you will not be granted any government support. This is the first step to apply for a permanent Contributory Parent visa (subclass 143). It will help you to ease the cost over a number of years. You can be in or outside Australia while you apply for this visa.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be sponsored, which in this case is usually by an eligible child who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen
  • •  You must not hold a Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 870)
  • •  You must meet the balance-of-family test
  • •  You must meet the health and character requirement

Contributory Parent visa (subclass 143) is a permanent visa that lets a parent of a settled Australian citizen or an Australian permanent resident or an eligible New Zealand citizen settle in Australia.

You can move to Australia as a permanent resident, and even sponsor eligible family members to come to Australia in future. You are eligible to enroll in Australia’s public health care scheme, Medicare. You can be in or outside Australia while applying for this visa. You can apply for this visa as a retiree too.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be sponsored, which in this case is usually by an eligible child who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen
  • •  You must not hold a Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 870)
  • •  You must meet the balance-of-family test
  • •  You must be able to obtain assurance of support
  • •  You must meet the health and character requirement

 

Note: You don’t need to be sponsored, meet the balance-of-family test and obtain assurance of support if you are applying as a retiree.

Parent visa (subclass 103) is a permanent visa that lets a parent of a settled Australian citizen or an Australian permanent resident or an eligible New Zealand citizen settle in Australia.

You can move to Australia as a permanent resident, and even sponsor eligible family members to come to Australia in future. You are eligible to enroll in Australia’s public health care scheme, Medicare. You can be in or outside Australia while applying for this visa. You can apply for this visa as a retiree too.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be sponsored, which in this case is usually by an eligible child who is an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen
  • •  You must not hold a Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 870)
  • •  You must meet the balance-of-family test
  • •  You must be able to obtain assurance of support
  • •  You must meet the health and character requirement

 

Note: You don’t need to be sponsored, meet the balance-of-family test and obtain assurance of support if you are applying as a retiree.

Sponsored Parent visa (subclass 870) is a temporary visa that lets a parent of a settled Australian citizen or an Australian permanent resident or an eligible New Zealand citizen visit Australia for 3 or 5 years, as granted on the visa.

You can extend your stay tenure for a maximum period of 10 years by applying for further visas. However, you cannot work while under this visa.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must have an approved Parent sponsor
  • •  You must be the biological and/or legal parent, adoptive parent, step-parent or parent-in-law of the Parent sponsor
  • •  You must be outside Australia when you apply for this visa, unless you have permission to apply in Australia
  • •  You must be a genuine temporary entrant
  • •  You must have, or have access to, adequate money to support yourself
  • •  You must meet the health and character requirement

Partner visas (subclass 820/801) are temporary and permanent visas for the partner or spouse of an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen, who are already in Australia, seeking to live here.

 

It is a two-step process; divided as Partner visa (subclass 820), which is a temporary visa, and Partner visa (subclass 801) which is a permanent visa.

Partner visas (subclass 309/100) are temporary and permanent visas for the partner or spouse of an Australian citizen or permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen, who are currently outside Australia, seeking to live here.

 

It is a two-step process; divided as Partner (Provisional) visa (subclass 309), which is a temporary visa, and Partner (Migrant) visa (subclass 100) which is a permanent visa.

Prospective Marriage visa (subclass 300) is a temporary visa that allows de-facto partners to enter Australia to marry their prospective spouse and apply for a Partner visa later. You can study or work while staying under this visa. 

You need to pay less for a Partner visa (subclass 820/801) if you apply for it while holding a Prospective Marriage visa.

 

Key eligibility criteria:

  • •  You must be in a genuine relationship with your partner
  • •  You must intend to marry your partner before the visa period ends
  • •  You must be sponsored, which in this case is usually by your prospective spouse
  • •  You must be 18 years or older
  • •  You must be overseas while applying for this visa
  • •  You must meet health and character requirement

Parent Sponsor is a vital requirement to lodge a Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa (subclass 870). You can be in or outside Australia while lodging your sponsorship application. To be a Parent Sponsor, one must:

  • Be over 18 years old
  • Be the child of the applicant (or the child’s spouse or de-facto partner)
  • Be an Australian citizen, or an Australian permanent resident or eligible New Zealand citizen residing in Australia for at least 4 years  
  • Not have been unlawful or held a Bridging visa (other than Bridging visa A, B, C) during the last 4 years
  • Have the taxable income of at least or greater than AUD 83,454.80 for the recently completed taxable income year 

 

Scope of your sponsorship:

  • Your household is limited to one sponsorship at a time
  • Your sponsorship can cover 2 parents per household at a time. It can be used any way:
  •     ° One or both of your parents
  •     ° One or both of your partner’s parents
  •     ° One of your parents and one of your partner’s parents

 

Obligations as a sponsor:

Failing to oblige these directives might lead to cancellation of your sponsorship and the parent’s visas.

  • Provide financial support and accommodation to the sponsored parent.
  • Alert the system in case of any changes in circumstances, eg: death or charged with crime
  • Pay back all the outstanding public health debts incurred by the sponsored parent in Australia

 

Sponsorship terminates if:

  • Sponsor’s permanent visa is cancelled
  • Sponsor dies
  • Sponsor withdraws their sponsorship
  • The prospective applicant does not apply for Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa within 6 months after the approval of sponsorship
  • The day the granted Sponsored Parent (Temporary) visa ends

Migration agents at Visa Alliance will help you through admissions, application review, navigating options, and changing courses.

Our expert migration agents will help and guide you through various assessment tests, sponsorships, and skilled graduate visas

Apart from this brief guide, any queries on this visa will be answered by our experts at Visa Alliance.

fields.heading: FAQ's
fields.question: Can I stay longer?
fields.answer:
You can only stay as per your course length. Primary school children of Years 1-4 can stay only up to a maximum period of 3 years.

If your student visa expires before your graduation, you might be eligible for a Visitor visa (subclass 600).

You can opt for other visas like Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485) or Skilled Recognition Graduate visa (subclass 476) after your graduation.

fields.question: Can I include my family members?
fields.answer: You can include your spouse/partner and your or your partner’s dependent child who has not turned 18 years old yet. The family members must meet all the health and character requirements.

fields.heading: FAQ's
fields.question: How long can I stay?
fields.answer:
Graduate Work Stream:
You cannot stay more than your specified tenure, that is 18 months for all applicants, and 5 years for Hong Kong passport holders. This visa is granted with multiple entries. You can enter and leave Australia as much as you want until the specified tenure.


Post-Study Work Stream (PSWS):
You cannot stay more than your specified tenure, that is 2 to 4 years for all applicants and 5 years for Hong Kong passport holders.

  • Bachelor degree (including honors): 2 years
  • Masters: 2 years
  • Masters by research: 3 years
  • Doctoral degree: 4 years
  • Hong Kong passport holders (successfully completed Bachelor, Masters or Doctoral degree): 5 years

fields.question: Can I extend this visa?
fields.answer: This visa is non-extendable in nature. Once the tenure ends, you need to apply for other types of skilled work visas. Current Temporary Graduate visa holders from Hong Kong are eligible for an extension of 5 years in addition to the time they have already been in Australia, and will also have a pathway to permanent residency after 5 years.

fields.question: Can I include my family members?
fields.answer: You can bring your immediate family members along with you as subsequent entrants through this visa. These family members must apply for the visa and must meet the health and character requirements.

fields.question: Does that require extra cost?
fields.answer: Beyond the cost for the main applicant, there is an additional charge for each family member who applies for the visa. You have to pay for health checks, police certificates and biometrics too.

fields.question: Can I apply for this visa while in Australia?
fields.answer:
You must hold an eligible substantive visa to apply for this visa while in Australia.

You can apply for a Special Purpose visa, or a Dependent Diplomatic (temporary) visa within 28 days of holding a Student visa or within 28 days of being notified by the Tribunal that your cancellation date has been set aside.

fields.heading: FAQ's
fields.question: Can I work or study while under this visa?
fields.answer:
You cannot work while under Student Guardian visa.

However, you can take an English Language Intensive Course for Overseas Students (ELICOS) for less than 20 hours per week, or any other study or training for less than 3 months

fields.question: Can I include any family members?

fields.question: Does that require extra cost?
fields.answer:
Beyond the cost for the main applicant, there is an additional charge for each family member who applies for the visa.

You have to pay for health checks, police certificates, and biometrics too

fields.question: Can I travel outside Australia during my stay?

You can travel outside Australia and return as many times as you wish, but only with the Student visa holder. 

If you wish to travel outside Australia without the Student visa holder, you must make alternative welfare arrangements.

fields.question: What types of occupational training are covered by this visa?

  • •  Occupational training required for registration
  • •  Occupational training to improve skills in an eligible occupation
  • •  Occupational training for capacity building overseas (this include overseas qualification, government support or professional)

fields.question: Does that require extra cost?

fields.answer: This is a permanent visa. You can stay in Australia indefinitely and become a permanent resident on the day you are granted a visa.

fields.question: Can I travel abroad as much as I want?
fields.answer: You can travel in and out of Australia as many times as you want for 5 years from the date you are granted a visa. After 5 years, you will need a Resident Return Visa (subclass 155 or 157) to re-enter Australia as a permanent resident.

fields.question: Does that require extra cost?

You can include your immediate family members in your application when you lodge your visa application or add them after you lodge your application but before it is granted. The family members must meet all the health and character requirements. 

There is an additional charge for each family member who applies for this visa.

fields.question: Does the age limit have any exceptions?
fields.answer: You must be below 45 when you are invited to apply for this visa. Your application can be invalid if you turn 45 after you submit your EOI but before you are invited to apply.

fields.question: Can I apply for this visa without nomination?
fields.answer:
You must be nominated by the state or territory government agencies to be invited to apply for this visa.

The nomination criteria for each state or territory government agency are different. Contact them directly to find out about their process.

fields.heading: FAQ's
fields.question: Can I include my family members?
fields.answer:
You can include your immediate family members in your application when you lodge your visa application or add them after you lodge your application but before it is granted.

If you are under 18 years old, you can include a parent or members of the family unit of that parent.

The family members must meet all the health and character requirements.

fields.question: Does that require extra cost?
fields.answer:
Beyond the cost for the main applicant, there is an additional charge for each family member who applies for the visa. 

Applicants might have to pay an extra charge of AUD 4,890 as a second installment for the family members of 18 years or older with less than functional English. This will only be applied if you are granted a visa.

fields.question: Can I travel abroad as much as I want?
fields.answer: You can travel in and out of Australia as many times as you want for 5 years from the date you are granted a visa. After 5 years, you will need a Resident Return Visa (subclass 155 or 157) to re-enter Australia as a permanent resident.

fields.question: Is there any limit for this visa?
fields.answer: For the Global Talent pathway of subclass 858, there is a limit of 15,000 visas only for the financial year 2021-2022.

fields.heading: Tourist Stream (Apply in Australia)
fields.question: Can I work under this visa?
fields.answer: You cannot work while on this visa. You can choose other visas if you wish to work here in Australia.

fields.question: Do I need this visa while on a cruise?
fields.answer: You must have this visa while entering Australia during a cruise.

fields.question: Can I include family members?
fields.answer: You cannot include family members in your application. Any members desiring to visit Australia must submit their own application.

fields.question: Does that require extra cost?
fields.answer:
Every applicant for this visa must pay their own charge.

You might have to pay extra for health checks, police certificates, and biometrics.

fields.heading: Tourist Stream (Apply outside Australia)
fields.question: Can I work under this visa?
fields.answer: You cannot work while on this visa. You can choose other visas if you wish to work here in Australia.

fields.question: Do I need this visa while on a cruise?
fields.answer: You must have this visa while entering Australia during a cruise.

fields.question: Can I stay longer?
fields.answer:
You can stay for the period of time specified in your visa.

If you are the parent or step-parent of an Australian citizen or permanent resident, and you meet all the visa criteria, you might be granted a longer stay of 18 months. You cannot stay more than 12 consecutive months in Australia.

fields.heading: Sponsored Family Stream
fields.question: Can I work under this visa?
fields.answer: You cannot work while on this visa. You can choose other visas if you wish to work here in Australia.

fields.question: Can I travel as much as I want while on this visa?
fields.answer:
You can travel in and out of Australia as many times as you want if it is granted on your visa.

If your visa has a single entry clause, you can leave Australia but cannot re-enter. You must apply for another visa to enter again.

fields.heading: Business Visitor Stream
fields.question: Can I work under this visa?
fields.answer: You cannot work while on this visa. You can choose other visas if you wish to work here in Australia.

fields.question: I hold an ABTC. Do I need to still apply for this visa?
fields.answer:
You might already be granted a Visitor visa (subclass 600) Business Visitor stream if you hold an Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) Business Travel Card (ABTC).

If allowed, you can enter Australia for a short period of time for business purposes or tourist activities for up to 5 years from the date of issue.

fields.heading: Approved Destination Status Stream
fields.question: Can I stay longer?
fields.answer: You cannot stay longer than the specified period of time in your grant letter. You must enter and leave Australia with your approved tour group.

fields.question: Can I include my family members?
fields.answer: You cannot include your family members in your application. Every interested member must apply for their own visa.

fields.heading: Frequent Traveller Stream
fields.question: Can I stay longer?
fields.answer:
You cannot stay longer than the specified period of 3 months each time you enter Australia.

You can only stay for up to 12 months in total of any 24 months period.

fields.question: Can I include my family members?
fields.answer: You cannot include your family members in your application. Every interested member must apply for their own visa.

fields.question: Is there a time limit for the de-facto relationship?
fields.answer: You must be in a de-facto relationship with your partner for at least 12 months immediately before applying for the visa.

fields.question: Can I include my family members?
fields.answer: You can include a dependent child or children when you apply for this visa. They must hold a Dependent Child visa (subclass 445) and be in Australia.

fields.question: Does that require extra cost?
fields.answer:
Beyond the cost for the main applicant, there is an additional charge for each family member who applies for the visa. But there is no charge for Dependent Child visa (subclass 445). 

You have to pay for their health check, police check, and biometrics too.

fields.question: Do I require a different health insurance?
fields.answer:
Depending on your circumstances, you might be eligible to enroll in Australia’s public health care system. 

If you are not eligible for that, you are recommended to have your own health insurance while you are in Australia.

fields.question: Can I travel as much as desired?
fields.answer:
If you have a temporary Partner visa (subclass 820), you can travel in and out of Australia as much as desired within the time your visa is valid.

After the first 5 years, you must have a Resident Return visa (RRV) to re-enter Australia as a permanent citizen. If you apply for Australian citizenship, you do not require any visa to re-enter. You can use your Australian passport.

fields.question: Is there any relationship requirement for the relationship?

De-facto partners must be in a relationship for at least 12 months immediately before applying for the visa.

fields.title: Study In Australia
fields.description:
Why Study in Australia

  1. Discover how to be an innovative, agile thinker

Australian universities, colleges and schools are committed to equipping you with practical skills and knowledge to help you succeed in your chosen industry. As global demand booms for entrepreneurial and innovative thinkers, Australian education providers have re-engineered their approaches to teaching and learning to inspire thought-leading creativity among students in every discipline.

  1. Top Quality Universities

Australia is setting international standards for excellence in education. International students have a wide variety of choice when it comes to studying. It is home to 3 universities in total. It’s a case of quality as well as quantity, with six Australian universities raking in the internationally renowned top 100.

If you’re looking for unbiased proof that Australian universities truly are world-class, look at independent global rankings such as Times Higher Education, QS and Shanghai Rankings. These organisations consistently rank Australian institutions in the world’s top 100 universities year after year.

  1. Gain work experience while you study

Australian institutions provide an education designed to help you succeed in the global workforce. An Australian qualification will make you very attractive to potential employers in Australia, at home and around the world.

Some Australian universities offer internships or work opportunities to their students. If this is the option that interests you, be sure to reach us to facilitate your journey. Also, professional network while you study. Once you complete your degree, you may also be eligible to stay and work in Australia.

While studying, you can work up to 20 hours per week during the semester and full-time during the semester break. This can be a great way to find study-related work or simply pay for your lifestyle in Australia.

  2. Access extensive student support services

Australia's Education Services for Overseas Students (ESOS ACT) framework enforces by law the best-practice protection for the rights of international students studying in Australia.

  1. Safety is Australia’s priority

Australian cities have some of the lowest crime rates in the world, and our streets and public spaces are open and safe. There are many options for accommodation: you can live in purpose-built student villages, homestays, private rentals, share-houses, or boarding school accommodation.

  1. Feel welcome in diverse society

Australia is a friendly and welcoming country. Our nation values individual freedoms, and the rights of citizens and visitors are protected under a transparent legal system.

We are also a multicultural society with respect for others no matter who they are or where they come from. Did you know almost 30% of Australians are born overseas? This has made our country rich with nationalities and cultures from all over the world.

When you study in Australia, you will join more than 800 thousand international students from 192 countries who have been welcomed into Australian life.

  1. Vibrant Australia’s great outdoors

With a unique mix of thriving cities and regional centres, vast open spaces and spectacular landscapes, it’s no wonder Australia attracts people from all over the world.

The first thing you will notice when you land in Australia is our fresh air and blue skies. We have a long history of protecting the beauty and sustainability of our environment. The result? Clean and sustainable cities and regional centres with plenty of green spaces and relatively low air pollution.

Our diverse natural environment offers a range of experiences – you can relax on our golden beaches, venture into our national parks to see our unique plants and animals and explore the untamed outback.

Australian institutions also place great importance on teaching students the value of sustainability and how to apply it in all areas of industry.

  1. High standard of living

Australian cities are consistently ranked as some of the most liveable in the world. Our quality of education, healthcare, transport, infrastructure, and government services are rated well above international averages.

Australia is a technologically advanced country with a strong, globally competitive economy. You will enjoy all the benefits of high-quality services, transportation and infrastructure in our towns and cities.

  1. Fantastic Work opportunities

Our educational institutions make students work-ready and understand what it takes to succeed in the global workforce. An Australian qualification will make you a very attractive potential employee to employers in Australia, at home and around the world.

Lucky for you, Visa Alliance understands this problem and sympathises with your cause. We are a company that is dedicated to helping with your relocation needs to Australia, whatever they may be.

We are a next-generation immigration firm/consulting company that provides a host of services under one roof, for anything pertaining to visas for Australia. We consist of a team of professionals, including migration and educational experts, who specialise in the migrations laws of Australia. Our skilled workforce often goes over and beyond to understand the needs of our customers, whether inside or outside Australia.
 

We help with most visas, like student visas, partner visas, temporary work visas, permanent skilled migration, and support them with a host of services that make the entire application, acceptance, and migration process so much easier for our clients. Being professionals, we have undergone the process ourselves and understood the problems faced by the everyday person, and tried to solve this huge divide between immigration, and someone applying without a good idea about the whole process.

We hope you chose us, and help make your transition to The Land Down Under as easy and hassle-free as possible.
